export const batch148 = {
  'intuitive-eating.json': {
    base: { id: 'intuitive-eating', title: 'Intuitive Eating', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781662110488 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Intuitive Eating rests on listening to your body and mind',
        text: "Most diets end in failure, and the brief relief they bring is an illusion. Restrictive eating damages the body, fuels eating disorders, and triggers painful cycles of weight gain. Yet people blame themselves and keep searching for the next diet.\n\nGood nutrition is not about rigid rules. Real nourishment means steady intake of vegetables, fruits, grains, and whole foods, with sweets enjoyed in moderation rather than feared. The deeper question is whether constant control is truly healthy. Nutritionists Evelyn Tribole and Elyse Resch argue that harmony comes from understanding what your body actually needs. When you learn to read your own signals, health improves and life feels lighter.\n\nIntuitive Eating, beloved by readers of the New York Times and Wall Street Journal, is a guide to accepting your body and releasing guilt after every meal. You already know when you are hungry and when you have had enough. The mind and body send signals all day, and most people overlook them. Work crowds out meals, parties pull you toward extra slices of pizza, and guilt follows. By practicing intuitive eating, you reclaim your attention and feel at home in your own skin.\n\nThis approach is not the absence of structure. It is the skill of listening inward and honoring what you feel.\n\nFrom this summary you will learn how to pick foods based on what your body asks for, give weight to the pleasure of eating, respect feelings of hunger and fullness, and appreciate the body you live in.\n\nA reminder: talk with your doctor before making major changes to your eating habits.",
        wordCount: 333
      },
      {
        title: 'Diets promise change but usually leave damage behind',
        text: "Dieting harms the body and warps the way you see yourself. For many, dieting becomes an obsession, and people will try every method while ignoring medical warnings. After each crash, they return to restriction, certain that this is the only path to looking right. The hidden costs add up fast.\n\nCravings grow when foods are forbidden, so the more you avoid a treat the louder it calls. When a diet ends, old habits return along with extra weight, and harsh self-criticism follows. Confidence takes a hit. Social life suffers because restaurant meals and parties become minefields. Metabolism slows as the body learns to run on less. Reliance on coffee and energy drinks creeps in. In the worst cases, eating disorders like anorexia and bulimia take root.\n\nMedia and online networks push diets constantly, selling narrow beauty standards. Bloggers and celebrities post polished photos. Fitness trainers shame anyone whose body does not match the ideal. Restrictions feed eating disorders that bring physical pain, emotional turmoil, and sometimes depression.\n\nConsider whether you recognize yourself in any of these patterns. Reading ingredient lists at every restaurant, counting every calorie, feeling guilty over a sweet bun. Starting a new diet each Monday, breaking it by Wednesday, and blaming yourself again. Skipping meals during busy days without noticing.\n\nDieting wears the body down. When food becomes scarce, the body fights to store energy. Researchers at the University of California tracked many dieters and found that about two-thirds gained more weight afterward than they had lost at the start.\n\nYour body reads food refusal as the threat of starvation.\n\nThe diet industry thrives on this cycle. The global weight loss market is expected to reach two hundred seventy-eight billion dollars by 2023.",
        wordCount: 388
      },
      {
        title: 'The starting move is releasing the dieter mindset',
        text: "Learning to eat intuitively is a form of freedom, and it unfolds in clear stages. First comes readiness, the honest wish to live better. Then self-exploration, the practice of listening to the body's quiet cues until it becomes second nature. From that attention grows food intuition, the ability to tell the difference between light and fierce hunger, between pleasant fullness and a stuffed belly. Eventually you learn to handle feelings without reaching for excess food. The final stage is awakening, a state of inner peace, freedom from rules, and the ease of choosing foods that truly serve your health and mood.\n\nThe first principle of Intuitive Eating is to stop dieting for good. As long as you chase a miracle cure for weight loss, you keep harming your health. Any system built on restriction and promising fast results is selling a lie.\n\nDieting creates the feeling of control, not the reality.\n\nLetting go of dietary rules spares you the emptiness that follows each ended plan. A few shifts can change the pattern. Put the scale away. Weight shifts for many reasons, and the drop on a strict plan often reflects water loss, since water makes up roughly seventy percent of lean mass.\n\nRecall how you actually felt during and after diets. The lightness and control were imagined. Real life during dieting brought eating swings, constant hunger, weakness, and rarely the result you wanted. Hold that truth in mind.\n\nFall in love with the body you have and free your spirit. Stop comparing yourself with others. Instead of hunting flaws, notice what you love and put it forward. Keep a gratitude journal and thank yourself daily for accepting and appreciating your body.\n\nAs long as money can be made, new gimmicks and diets will keep appearing, as Evelyn Tribole and Elyse Resch have noted.",
        wordCount: 377
      },
      {
        title: 'Honor hunger with the same care you once gave to diets',
        text: "Hunger is a vital message from your body, so ignoring it carries a cost. When food is restricted, the body reads the situation as danger and demands fuel, which is why dieters swing between desperation and despair.\n\nGood nutrition powers every system in the body. The longer you starve, the more your body craves carbohydrates, its main fuel. When the diet does not deliver enough, the body pulls carbs from other sources, including muscle. That is like pulling logs from the walls of a wooden house to feed the fire. The ability to feel natural, gentle hunger supports health and helps prevent weight gain. Watch for early signs such as a growling stomach, light dizziness, trouble focusing, low energy, or a dull headache.\n\nTry treating food as a friend. Psychologist Fritz Heider pointed out that avoiding a particular food creates a sense of deprivation.\n\nA study at Northwestern University compared people who diet constantly with those who never restrict. Both groups tasted and rated three ice creams and could eat as much as they wanted. The non-dieters ate moderate portions. The dieters piled their bowls high, savoring the taste of freedom.\n\nStop sorting foods into clean and dirty categories. No single food makes the body gain or lose weight on its own. Begin allowing yourself the foods you crave. Notice what truly satisfies you at a given moment. There is no reason to schedule clean eating days and return to restriction. When forbidden foods become ordinary, the obsession with them fades.\n\nThe surest way to stop obsessing over a forbidden food is to start eating it.",
        wordCount: 354
      },
      {
        title: 'Build a friendly relationship with food and enjoy every bite',
        text: "Becoming friends with food follows a simple path. Begin by writing a list of foods and dishes you crave most often. Mark the ones you already eat and separate the ones you treat as off-limits. Then allow yourself to buy and enjoy one of those off-limits items, ideally by ordering it at a restaurant. While eating, notice every sensation: taste, texture, warmth. If the food feels good, welcome it back into your routine whenever you want. Finally, keep a small stock of those foods at home. The moment you know you can have them anytime, their grip loosens.\n\nWhen calories and pounds stop running the show, mindful eating takes the wheel. Train your instincts by noticing the thoughts and feelings that show up before, during, and after a meal.\n\nFullness deserves the same attention as hunger. Clean eating culture often pushes the idea that a meal ends only when the plate is empty. Real fullness shows up much sooner. Practice spotting it by pausing during the meal to check in with yourself. After eating, notice whether you feel light and content or stuffed and heavy. Track those notes in a journal or spreadsheet. Over time you will recognize your own threshold for comfortable fullness and stop at that point. Foods that tend to satisfy without tipping into excess include tuna, chicken, beans, cheese, whole grain bread, and yogurt.\n\nJapanese culture treats the joy of food as central to a full life. Psychologist Abraham Maslow taught that unmet needs quietly injure us.\n\nA nutrient-packed salad helps no one if the body is asking for meat.\n\nEat slowly and savor every bite. Pay attention to flavor, texture, aroma, color, and temperature. Choose foods whose qualities match what you need right now. Even a sushi lover can crave cooked food on certain days. Build variety into meals, and trust yourself to say no when an item does not appeal.",
        wordCount: 395
      },
      {
        title: 'Bringing Intuitive Eating into your daily life',
        text: "Food should not be a tool for solving problems or numbing emotions. There are many ways to ease anxiety, sadness, anger, and boredom, and overeating is not one of them. Food can distract from pain for a short while, yet it never solves the cause. Emotional eating leaves guilt and heaviness behind. Some people also use food to revisit happy memories, eating extra portions of childhood favorites. Minding a bag of chips during a dull task or rewarding yourself with treats after finishing work also counts as emotional eating.\n\nMany non-food options lift the spirit and care for the self at the same time. A few examples include visits to a sauna or jacuzzi, dancing to favorite music, watching a good movie, meditating or practicing yoga, playing with a pet, a trip to a beauty salon, time with friends, and writing feelings down in a journal.\n\nEven curling up in bed with a stuffed toy beats compulsive overeating when stress hits.\n\nFighting your body is fighting your mind. Respecting the body means meeting its basic needs with dignity.\n\nChildren can learn intuitive eating early. Babies read their own cues well, so forcing a child to clean the plate teaches them to ignore their own wisdom. Parents hold real authority, and that authority works best when it is gentle. Invite children to tell you when they feel hungry and respect their sense of fullness. Cook new dishes together and pack nourishing snacks like fresh fruit, vegetables, nuts, or hummus for school. Remember that children go through changing appetites, often needing more food after active play.\n\nIntroduce the value of food early. Teach children that food gives them energy to play, helps them sleep well, and supports clear thinking at school, as Evelyn Tribole and Elyse Resch suggest.",
        wordCount: 368
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: "Sad numbers tell part of the story. About thirty percent of women would trade a year of life for the promise of an ideal body. Nearly half of women have been bullied over their looks at some point. Accepting and loving yourself takes time, patience, and many restarts, yet it pays off.\n\nIntuitive Eating asks for respect for every body and a flexible outlook on food. The phrase eat whenever, whatever, and however much I want sounds chaotic, yet in practice it means freedom grounded in real hunger and fullness cues. Years of dieting take time to undo, but the joy of eating what you love returns with steady practice. When you believe in your right to enjoy food, life without limits becomes possible.\n\nA few ways to honor your new bond with your body include buying new comfortable clothes and underwear that lift your confidence, stepping off the scale for good, and unfollowing any accounts that stir comparison. Move your body in ways that feel good, from taking the stairs to dancing in the kitchen.\n\nRepeat these affirmations each day. My body deserves good nutrition. My body deserves kind treatment. I want to wear clothes that feel good on me. My body is worthy of love and respect.\n\nA short weekly quiz can track your progress. Answer yes to statements like: it is easy for me to notice hunger and fullness, I trust my body when deciding to eat, and no foods are forbidden for me. Answer no to statements like: I still follow diet rules, I eat to silence bad feelings, and I scold myself for eating what I think is unhealthy.",
        wordCount: 381
      }
    ]
  },
  'invisible-women.json': {
    base: { id: 'invisible-women', title: 'Invisible Women', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781662216599 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Data is a decisive argument in the fight for equality',
        text: "Fewer conflicts and better education share a surprising link. Both follow from greater participation by women in policy roles. The track record of female leaders is striking. When women join talks between warring countries, the chance that peace holds for at least fourteen years climbs by thirty-five percent. Portugal has raised school spending as more women entered parliament. Even with such results, many male-led fields still resist gender equality.\n\nMen often push back when they hear about protests against discrimination, saying gender is discussed too much. They believe the world is already equal. That view is understandable, since men rarely see or hear about the daily gaps women face. Those gaps come from a data problem with two roots. First, researchers collect less data about women's lives, and we will look at why soon. Second, even when studies include women, they rarely break out the results by sex.\n\nWhy does this matter? Data shapes decisions and drives change. When Google saw that new mothers were leaving at twice the rate of other employees, the company extended paid maternity leave. Departures dropped by half. As long as half of humanity stays invisible in the numbers, their needs will keep slipping through the cracks.\n\nClosing the data gap can lift women's health, grow GDP, and reduce crime.\n\nLet us explore how data gaps hold societies back and survey approaches from around the world that tackle this problem. The findings are eye-opening.",
        wordCount: 268
      },
      {
        title: 'How data-led design saves lives',
        text: "If you ever wish smartphones would shrink, here is a small comfort. Designers say devices will not get larger, since they have hit the size limit for the average man's hand. It is a small window into how male defaults shape the things we use every day. The same bias explains why fitness trackers underestimate calories burned during housework and why makeup can confuse VR headsets. Some of these mismatches are minor annoyances, yet others cost lives.\n\nMost products default to male measurements.\n\nHave you ever wondered why women face a forty-seven percent higher risk of severe injury in car crashes than men? Crash test data hints at the cause. Test dummies stand one hundred seventy-seven centimeters tall and weigh seventy-six kilograms, matching a fairly average man. That dummy misses the shape of at least half the population. Adding a female dummy is not enough. Women tend to sit more upright and closer to the pedals. The data gap led engineers to treat that posture as unusual.\n\nA stubborn belief stops many men from seeing the blind spot in their designs. Rather than rethink the product, they blame the user. That is exactly what happened with clean cookstoves designed for low-income regions. Over seventy-five percent of households in South Asia rely on biomass such as wood or dried leaves for cooking. A single meal can take three hours or more. Women breathe fumes that rival the impact of smoking a hundred cigarettes a day, with deep costs to their health.\n\nWhen aid groups handed out clean stoves, the devices gathered dust. The designers had assumed women simply lacked education. Once they collected real data, they discovered the new stoves cooked more slowly and demanded constant watching. That was not workable for women juggling many tasks. In 2015, a research team built a tool that fits into traditional stoves, boosting airflow and cutting fumes. The new design has helped families in Kenya, India, and Ghana.\n\nBlaming users happens in wealthy countries too. One company faced criticism after its voice recognition software struggled with women's voices. Executives told users they simply needed to train more. The real cause was that the system had learned from audio recorded mostly by men.",
        wordCount: 401
      },
      {
        title: 'The transport system is biased against women',
        text: "Male defaults stretch well beyond products and into city planning. Transportation planning is heavily shaped by men, so routes follow the daily commute and peak hours. London's transit map looks like a spider web that gets workers downtown fast while making every other trip awkward. But who takes those other trips.\n\nThat assumption stuck around until Spanish researchers studied women's travel patterns. They found that trips for care, such as dropping children at school or visiting a doctor, happen about as often as work commutes. Adding routes that serve those trips makes economic sense. London's hopper fare is a workable compromise, letting riders use buses and trams freely for an hour. Women running daily errands benefit the most.\n\nMost car owners are men. In Rio de Janeiro, seventy-one percent of drivers are male.\n\nFocusing on commutes creates another blind spot. Governments are more willing to fund new roads than repair cracked sidewalks. Walkers with strollers feel the gap every day. That is another data problem.\n\nSnow removal reveals a similar pattern. Cities clear main arteries first, so icy conditions put many people at risk, and women are over-represented in injury reports. The Swedish city of Umeå calculated that sixty-nine percent of hospital visits in slippery weather involve women. Local authorities shifted priorities toward pedestrians and transit, and the change not only made streets safer but also saved money, since injuries and lost productivity are expensive.\n\nSnow is not the only danger on the move. Sexual harassment hangs over daily commutes. Studies from 2016 found that ninety percent of French women had experienced harassment while traveling. Most never reported it, expecting nothing to change. The data gap is vast. Some women have even quit jobs to avoid public transit.\n\nFixes exist. Conductors on board help, and so do small upgrades. Because crimes happen about three times more often at stops than on board, well-lit and transparent shelters can lift safety for everyone.",
        wordCount: 394
      },
      {
        title: 'Unpaid labor drastically affects women\'s income',
        text: "Recent research shows that working fifty hours a week hits men and women very differently. Men face lower depression risk, while women face a higher chance of serious illness. Even a forty-one to forty-five hour week can affect women's mental health. The gap is not about strength. Unpaid work, including housework and caregiving, drives the difference, and women handle seventy-five percent of that work worldwide. Health effects are only the start.\n\nPay and pensions take a hit. Bias is not the only reason women earn less. Many women, including forty-two percent in the UK, cut their hours to balance job and family. Caring for relatives shrinks lifetime earnings and weakens retirement benefits. Countries such as Brazil and Bolivia have introduced non-contributory pensions, a fix that helps women noticeably.\n\nThere is no such thing as a woman who doesn't work. There is only a woman who isn't paid for her work, as Caroline Criado-Perez has written.\n\nMaternity leave policies cost some women their jobs. An Australian study showed that paid leave for at least seven months after birth helps women return to work, yet no country delivers that fully. UK women receive a third of their salary for thirty-nine weeks. Croatia, in contrast, provides thirty weeks at full pay. Some firms now offer after-school or summer programs to keep mothers on staff, though flexible hours and remote work would do even more.\n\nWomen's labor participation lifts entire economies. The World Economic Forum names it as a major driver of European growth over the past decade.\n\nThe data gap around unpaid work hides the value of social investment. Governments tend to see care infrastructure as a cost, yet the opposite is true. Investing two percent of US GDP in construction could create seven and a half million jobs, and investing in care could create thirteen million. Such investment would also let many more mothers join the workforce and lift the country's GDP.\n\nWork brings other challenges beyond caregiving, and stories shared through the #MeToo movement show just how wide those problems run.",
        wordCount: 395
      },
      {
        title: 'Science used to misjudge gender differences',
        text: "Healthcare seems like a place where data would be solid, yet textbooks tell another story. Open a chapter on the respiratory or digestive system and there is rarely a mention of sex differences. Research papers follow the same pattern. After testing drugs only on men, scientists often claim the results will help women too. The picture is shifting. Modern research shows that every organ system has sex-specific traits, and diseases often show up differently across sexes. A few examples highlight the gap.\n\nThe immune system responds more strongly in women. Vaccines can trigger stronger reactions in women, and in 2014 researchers argued that influenza vaccines should be designed with sex in mind.\n\nSkin thickness differs. The female dermis is thinner, which means women face a higher risk of chemical exposure. Little research exists on how the mix of toxic substances in household products adds up for women.\n\nPain sensitivity varies. Men feel pain less sharply, so their experience became the medical norm. Doctors sometimes dismiss women's pain as emotional and prescribe antidepressants instead of real relief. Women end up consuming antidepressants at two and a half times the rate of men, even though research suggests men are more prone to depression.\n\nCommon symptoms do not always line up. The standard tuberculosis test relies on sputum, yet women rarely cough up the sample, which delays diagnosis.\n\nTreatment effects can flip. Search online for the impact of resistance training on people with hypertension and many sites warn about increased artery stiffness. That is true for men. For women, the same exercises lower blood pressure and have a smaller effect on stiffness.\n\nThe same drug can work in opposite directions for men and women, which raises an unsettling question: how many helpful treatments have been shelved because they failed in male trials.\n\nSome countries are tightening the rules. Federally funded trials in the United States, the European Union, and Australia now require researchers to include both sexes. The German Society of Epidemiology and the Canadian Institutes of Health Research ask researchers to factor in gender when designing studies.\n\nAnorexia may signal autism. Since men rarely develop anorexia, researchers missed this clue for years.",
        wordCount: 411
      },
      {
        title: 'Why women\'s participation in science is fundamental',
        text: "Gender inequality has eased compared with earlier decades, so why does the data gap remain? Psychology points to projection bias, the habit of assuming others share our habits and views.\n\nConvincing someone a need exists is hard when they do not feel that need themselves, as Caroline Criado Perez has observed.\n\nA field without diversity will always carry gaps, and science is a clear example. Women remain underrepresented in research worldwide. Gender bias shows up in many ways. For instance, journals accept more articles from women when reviewers cannot see the author's name, which is a worrying signal about double-blind review's absence.\n\nFunding and citations also tilt toward men. Consider Susan Wray, whose work predicts when a cesarean is the safer choice and raised the rate of safe vaginal births from sixty-seven percent to eighty-four percent. That breakthrough matters most in regions without reliable surgical care. Yet her grant application was turned down because reviewers called the project a low priority.\n\nFortunately, new organizations have stepped up to support female scientists, including the foundation started by Nobel laureate Christiane Nüsslein-Volhard.\n\nLifting the number of women in science and backing their ideas would shrink the data gap quickly.\n\nSTEM fields, including science, technology, engineering, and math, need particular attention. Only twenty-five percent of tech workers are women, and the long-term consequences worry many observers. Artificial intelligence mirrors and amplifies the biases of its makers. What does that look like in practice.\n\nSearch results for a programmer or other male-coded jobs tend to surface men's profiles first, because the algorithm treats them as more relevant. AI hiring tools can filter women out. Some tech platforms assume strong candidates spend time on manga sites, an interest that does not match many women's habits.\n\nLess biased models exist, and companies must choose to use them. With only eleven percent of tech executives being women, change will take time.",
        wordCount: 383
      },
      {
        title: 'Data alone is not enough; society should act on it',
        text: "In 2014, BI Norwegian Business School identified five qualities of influential leaders. Women outscored men in four of them. Even so, statistics on policymakers show that gender equality is far from reality. This gap slows economic growth and keeps the data gap alive. Findings only matter once we act on them.\n\nPolitics is a key area. Studies in the United States show that female legislators push harder for women's needs and rights, yet women make up less than a quarter of politicians worldwide. Quotas work, although many people treat them with suspicion. Some argue that equality should happen naturally. The evidence says otherwise.\n\nIn 1972, the Swedish Social Democratic Party suggested that electoral lists include more women. That step and similar ones barely moved the needle. In 1993, the party introduced a zipper quota, alternating men and women on each list. After that, women's representation climbed.\n\nEven now, a third of Sweden's female local politicians consider leaving office, since threats make the job unsustainable. Data confirms that this pattern repeats in many countries.\n\nThe fact that ninety-three percent of venture capitalists are men is bad news for women entrepreneurs. Venture capital drives tech startups, so this imbalance narrows support for women's projects. When Debbie Woskow co-founded AllBright to fund female innovators, her male colleagues dismissed the venture as charity. They were surprised to hear she planned to make money from it.\n\nBoston Consulting Group found that women-led startups receive over one million dollars less in funding than men-led ones, yet their revenues run higher.\n\nDisaster response is another front. Women suffer more in natural disasters, partly because of men's violence and gender inequality. In Sri Lanka, for example, parents rarely teach girls to swim or climb trees, treating those skills as male. Floods hit women harder as a result. Refugee camp planning benefits from women's input. The simple absence of separate bathrooms, a detail male planners often miss, raises the risk of violence against women.\n\nIn Bangladesh, women cannot go out alone and must travel with a male relative, which costs them precious minutes during evacuations.",
        wordCount: 404
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "Cecilia Payne-Gaposchkin discovered that stars are mostly hydrogen and helium, yet most textbooks never mention her name. Cave paintings in France and Spain often go unattributed to the women who created them. Many Americans know their country has not won the men's World Cup, but few realize that the women's national team has won it four times. These oversights are not accidents. They come from a culture shaped by the male perspective.\n\nMany parts of life, from devices to public spaces, were designed by men and for men. New efforts are changing that picture. Sweden introduced a month of parental leave that fathers must use or lose, and uptake rose sharply. South Korea and Iceland have adopted the same idea. In India, activists built a platform that flags unsafe districts and helps women pick safer transit routes. Several tech firms now use blind hiring systems, and they have hired more employees from non-traditional backgrounds as a result.\n\nInitiatives differ, yet most aim to close the representation gap. One person's success can lift many others. Women scientists tend to study issues that affect women, and women journalists are more likely to cover those findings.\n\nChange starts with the recognition that doing nothing keeps the imbalance in place. Everyone shares the same boat, and attention to others' needs helps us all.\n\nWatch TED Talks by women leaders and notice how they make change every day. Read a book about minorities to widen your view. Look up women's participation in your country's politics.",
        wordCount: 309
      }
    ]
  },
  'irresistible.json': {
    base: { id: 'irresistible', title: 'Irresistible', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781662310845 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Unfair stereotyping of addiction',
        text: "We tend to picture addiction in narrow terms. It is something that affects certain people we call addicts, a label that sets them apart. The word suggests a different category of person, one that may eventually recover but remains distinct. In reality, addiction grows mostly out of environment and circumstance.\n\nAddictive behaviors are not new, but they have spread, grown stronger, and become more accepted in recent years. Modern addictions do not always involve a substance, yet they deliver the same pull because they are built to be irresistible. Gambling and exercise addictions have long histories. Binge-watching and smartphone habits are newer arrivals.\n\nThe stigma around addiction keeps people from seeking help, and that is something to push back against.\n\nNo one is safe from addiction. It can reach anyone. Behavioral and substance addictions share more than people think. Both light up the same brain chemicals and feed the same needs, including the need to feel relevant, to feel stimulated, and to feel confident. When those needs go unmet, the door to addiction swings open.\n\nThis summary will walk through how to live alongside addictive activities that shape daily life without letting them take over. We will look at how to spot addictive patterns and soften their effect on happiness and well-being.\n\nThere isn't a bright line between addicts and the rest of us. We are all one product or experience away from developing our own addictions, as Adam Alter has written.\n\nLet us begin this journey into the nature of addiction.",
        wordCount: 278
      },
      {
        title: 'The problem of behavioral addictions',
        text: "Modern usage often treats addiction as a bad habit. A behavior earns the label of addictive only when it causes serious disruption in someone's life or in the lives of people around them.\n\nWhen behavior becomes addictive, professional help is usually required.\n\nUnlike substance addiction, behavioral addiction does not involve tobacco, alcohol, or drugs. It arises when someone cannot resist a behavior and that behavior hurts the people around them.\n\nAddictions, obsessions, and compulsions are not the same. Addictions offer an immediate payoff, whether the user enjoys it or not. Obsessions and compulsions are harmful, often dangerous pursuits that are hard to break. A person caught in an obsession may feel that they have lost control, and specialists often need to step in.\n\nIn 2003, a team of seven Canadian psychologists, including Robert Vallerand, defined passion as a strong pull toward an activity that someone enjoys and pours time and energy into.\n\nHarmonious passions sit on the calm end. People pursue them without upending their lives. The activity fits naturally with the rest of their day.\n\nObsessive passions run hot and often cause harm. A person with an obsession cannot easily step away from the activity that fuels it, and that loss of control is what slips into behavioral addiction.\n\nA study published in the Industrial Psychology Journal looked at young adolescents and found that about seventy-four percent were moderate internet users, while less than one percent could be called addicts. The same study linked heavy internet use with anxiety and depression.",
        wordCount: 333
      },
      {
        title: 'How behavioral addictions work',
        text: "Behavioral addiction is the pull to repeat a rewarding activity that does not involve a substance. People sometimes call it a natural reward, even when it comes with negative consequences for the body, mind, relationships, or finances.\n\nAddictions to behavior take hold when biological processes are disturbed.\n\nAbout one in six adults struggles with poor sleep, often because blue light from devices pushes bedtime later.\n\nFor most of human history, blue light marked daytime and red light signaled night. The shift triggered sleep.\n\nDeep inside the brain, the pineal gland releases melatonin when darkness falls, the hormone that brings on sleepiness. People with insomnia sometimes take melatonin supplements. Blue light from phones and laptops slows that release, telling the body to stay alert. Studies show that addictive behaviors shift the brain in ways that mirror substance abuse.\n\nDim the lights and step away from screens an hour before bed to protect sleep.\n\nDrugs are appealing largely because they promise intense pleasure. The brain chemical behind that feeling is dopamine, a neurotransmitter linked to reward. Eating tasty food or having sex also sparks a small release of dopamine, and that release adds to the sense of pleasure and satisfaction.\n\nNormally, the brain releases dopamine in modest amounts. Substances and addictive behaviors can cause large spikes. At first, the rush feels great, but repeated surges push the brain to scale back its own production. The drop in dopamine drains the pleasure from everyday life. People chase bigger hits to feel better, and that cycle feeds addiction.",
        wordCount: 306
      },
      {
        title: 'The ingredients of behavioral addiction',
        text: "Behavioral addictions often start the same way drug or alcohol addictions do. Natural brain chemicals such as dopamine flood the system whenever someone engages in the activity. Many people scroll through social media or play video games without sliding into addiction. Vulnerable people end up craving the activity and returning to it at harmful levels.\n\nSetting goals is one of the strongest motivators the brain knows.\n\nGoals drive the mind toward specific outcomes. Beating a high score in a game or hitting a friend count on Facebook are simple goals that quietly hook people into unhealthy patterns.\n\nWhat makes behavioral addiction so hard to treat is that the activities often look normal. Staying off the internet, for instance, is nearly impossible in modern life.\n\nHumans are social creatures, so making friends online, gaming, and browsing the web fit a real need. Problems appear when screen time crowds out face-to-face contact. Behavioral addiction eats into the real experiences that young people need to grow.\n\nThe need to see the world as others do, often called social confirmation, shows that we belong to a group. Through evolution, group members had a better chance of surviving than loners.\n\nWhen social bonds are missing, people suffer deeply. Researchers call it the social death penalty. The pain lingers, and even the memory of being left out can bring it back. Many people say that social exclusion ranks among their worst memories.",
        wordCount: 310
      },
      {
        title: 'The threat of child addiction',
        text: "The early years of a child's life shape mental, social, and physical health. Children are more vulnerable to addiction than adults because they have fewer inner brakes. Without steady guidance, addictions can take root early.\n\nVideo games, social media, and television are the most common childhood addictions.\n\nHilarie Cash, a therapist who specializes in addiction and the author of Video Games and Your Kids, advises against any screen exposure for children under two. She argues that early interactions should be simple, social, personal, and tangible. The first two years matter most for learning how to engage with the world. Cash also suggests limiting television until children reach elementary school.\n\nCash recommends tight limits on screen time so that children can pour energy into sleep, physical play, family time, and mental growth.\n\nThe American Academy of Pediatrics adds a careful frame. Young children learn best through real-world contact. Rather than only restricting screens, the AAP offers three rules for sensible screen use.\n\nHelp children connect what they see on screens with what they encounter in real life. This transfer of learning boosts understanding. A child who sees a dog on screen and meets one on the street begins to grasp that dogs exist in many settings.\n\nActive engagement beats passive watching. An app that invites a child to act, recall, decide, and talk with a parent does more than a TV show that demands nothing back.\n\nContent matters. Parents should curate what children watch and choose material that adds something real.",
        wordCount: 337
      },
      {
        title: 'The nature of behavioral patterns',
        text: "Behavioral patterns describe the way a person or group responds to internal and external cues. They vary from person to person. What hooks one individual may leave another cold.\n\nPeople also differ in their ability to resist temptation. Those who white-knuckle their way through addictive situations fail more often than those who steer clear of the situation in the first place.\n\nPsychologist Wendy Wood of the University of Southern California points out that willpower is not about staring down a plate of cookies. A good habit is to avoid places where the cookies are sitting out. The problem is not a lack of willpower. Many forces in modern life actively weaken self-control.\n\nKeep your workspace tidy and block out time for tasks that matter.\n\nChoosing a positive path means swapping a harmful habit for something that delivers a similar reward. The golden rule is that different strokes work for different people. A method that helps one person may fail another. Finding the right fit starts with asking what made the original behavior so rewarding. The same surface behavior can hide very different needs.\n\nWe need losses and difficulties to some degree, because without them the thrill of success weakens with each new victory, as Adam Alter has noted.\n\nPicture yourself trying to avoid Instagram. When the urge hits, you can say, I am not allowed to use Instagram, or you can say, I choose not to use Instagram. Behavioral design accepts that pure avoidance is hard. You cannot quit your phone, but you can use it less. Checking email is part of life, but you can refresh less often.\n\nSet aside clear time for work and tech, and another block for rest and friends. Many addictive tools are intrusive, so staying alert matters.",
        wordCount: 372
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "In an era when addictive technology sits at the center of daily life, no one is truly safe from addiction. Pure willpower rarely works, yet other paths exist. We can limit addictive activities and build habits that support healthy behavior.\n\nUnderstanding behavioral addiction is the first step toward reducing its harm. Addictions are dangerous because they push aside the things that give life meaning, from career goals to basic self-care and friendships. We have to work deliberately to recover the balance that existed before email, wearables, social media, smartphones, and instant streaming.\n\nAs social creatures, we need real relationships with the people around us. Online friendships, while appealing to young gamers and internet fans, miss something important. They cannot replace the experience of sitting beside someone and sharing a real conversation.\n\nMost of the world's population depends on some substance or behavior. The most common form of dependence is behavioral, and almost everyone wrestles with one behavior or another. The way out is to understand how, why, and when the habit started, then work step by step to escape it.\n\nA few simple steps help. Cut back on phone and TV use before bed to protect sleep. Choose real-world activities over virtual ones. Notice what triggers your habits and steer clear of those situations when you can. Remember that habit change looks different for everyone, so find what works for you.",
        wordCount: 300
      }
    ]
  },
  'is-it-just-me.json': {
    base: { id: 'is-it-just-me', title: 'Is It Just Me?', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781662429922 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Growing up comes without a survival guide',
        text: "Comedian Miranda Hart argues that life refuses to ship with a manual. We all crash through strange, undignified moments and must improvise on the spot. Picture the most recent time you stood there, face flushed, brain spinning, with no idea how to escape the situation gracefully. The roadmap was missing.\n\nSuch awkward encounters pepper every day. There is no rulebook to consult.\n\nAs a teenager, Miranda assumed she was uniquely cursed with a talent for embarrassment. She would frantically over-explain to bystanders, insisting her bizarre behavior had been deliberate. Watching Dirty Dancing only deepened her kinship with the film character, that is, Baby, who fumbles through the famous watermelon moment.\n\nEventually, Miranda realized plenty of adults share the same feeling. Still, she kept wanting to chart her own course, sidestepping the unspoken rules that seem to govern everyone else.\n\nThe advice she offers is plain. Laugh at the things that mark you out. Stop pretending you fit some imaginary mold. Most of us feel the same disconnect.\n\nMastering the art of laughing at yourself and standing your ground in awkward moments is a real skill. Miranda has clearly developed it. She uses the stories in Is It Just Me to remind readers that they are in good company.\n\nBeyond standup, Miranda played Chummy in the BBC drama Call the Midwife, giving her a second career lane.",
        wordCount: 323
      },
      {
        title: 'Your music taste does not need a label',
        text: "Almost everyone likes music, yet settling into your own taste takes time. Miranda openly admits she adores music yet never quite slides into the cool crowd. Her track record of musical missteps is rich. Once, when asked about Kanye West, she thought the questioner was hunting for a Tube station near Cockfosters. Another time, she pictured Tinchy Stryder as a line of children's sneakers.\n\nIn theory, deep music knowledge makes you look interesting, but plenty of listeners never find their footing. The healthier move is to enjoy whatever you enjoy, regardless of the era or the genre.\n\nMiranda also flags that her height makes dancing at concerts awkward. During a wedding, she attempted to join the mosh pit and accidentally brought down the marquee pole.\n\nThe takeaway is simple. Feeling like the odd one out at a gig is normal. Far more people share that discomfort than you might think.\n\nFor readers who suspect they missed the music gene, Miranda's reassurance is direct. Joy is every bit as valuable as looking cool, she says.",
        wordCount: 208
      },
      {
        title: 'Pastimes often vanish as we age',
        text: "When was the last time someone asked about your hobbies and your mind went completely blank. The question seems innocent, yet Miranda dreads it. Her standard reply is movies, and then the awkward math begins, since she has not entered a cinema in nearly a year.\n\nSome adults carry childhood interests into careers and profit from them. Far more quietly let those interests slip away. The reason is uncomfortable. Past the age of thirteen, doing something for fun only feels acceptable if you show real talent.\n\nThe activities you loved as a child rarely make it to your teen and adult years. If natural skill is missing, the activity fades. Practice enjoying things for the act itself, not for the competition.\n\nMiranda adored ballet, but at thirteen she had to admit she would never be Darcy Bussell. The other girls in her class progressed to higher levels. At that age, society quietly tells you that participation requires real ability. By your twenties, your list of hobbies has thinned to the point where you recycle the same three answers, such as reading, traveling, and swimming.\n\nMany people sign up for a new pastime each January, yet the effort usually stalls. By March the project has barely started and three months feel lost. Miranda suggests dropping the urge to impress with a fancy list and just doing what you enjoy.",
        wordCount: 325
      },
      {
        title: 'Routine work can still deliver quiet fun',
        text: "Few people land their dream job straight out of school. Many do not know what they want for years afterward. Miranda was no exception. She spent roughly a decade in office roles, gazing out of windows and wondering whether she would ever reach the work she loved.\n\nIf your career is still foggy, relax. Clarity tends to arrive once you understand your own tastes and limits.\n\nMiranda found the start of working life disorienting. School rewards boundary-pushing, while work prizes order. She quickly saw that her playful humor would not translate well to a Monday meeting. Miranda points out that no parent ever warns you about that gap, so the reality feels like a cold shower.\n\nEven after years in low-level office roles, Miranda treats that stretch as a gift. Time near the bottom teaches you who you are, how the world functions, and gives you the confidence to step forward. It also introduces you to colleagues and builds resilience through tough stretches.\n\nPlenty of lighthearted moments hide in jobs that put you around other people and give you room to grow.\n\nMiranda Hart has publicly defended the joys of office life, insisting that even disappointing turns still hold room for laughter.",
        wordCount: 282
      },
      {
        title: 'Taking yourself seriously as a woman has little to do with grooming',
        text: "Miranda once heard from a friend that she was not treating herself as a serious woman because she lugged a battered backpack instead of an expensive purse. The comment made her pause. Why should the bag define her. Do men face the same tests before they count as serious men.\n\nPush back on the unspoken rules that supposedly define a woman. A new handbag is not a passport to acceptance.\n\nMiranda chooses to invest her hours in personality, humor, and craft rather than in front of the mirror. Part of that comes from never fitting into what she calls the beautiful crowd.\n\nAt her boarding school, Miranda and her circle were labeled the normals. They were neither the beautifuls nor the friends of the beautifuls, and they liked it that way. Looking back, she treats that label as a small gift.\n\nConstantly being the pretty one tends to lock people into that single role, since that becomes the only lens through which anyone sees them. Those outside that lens get pushed to develop other muscles. They have space to study themselves, sharpen their talents, and pick up new ones. By their twenties, they are ready to step into the world with the full kit of skills they have built. The pretty crowd is still there, doing what they have always done.\n\nAnyone who never slotted into the in crowd should count the blessings rather than chasing a label that never fit.\n\nBelonging matters when you are young, but a little age teaches you that simply being yourself is far more important.",
        wordCount: 295
      },
      {
        title: 'Honor your body at every size',
        text: "Modern culture pushes a narrow body ideal, yet real bodies arrive in every shape and dimension.\n\nMost readers absorb that pressure without noticing, and Miranda needed time before she could see it clearly. Her teenage years were awkward because of her height, but now she wears it lightly. She notices the upsides and the downsides and accepts the whole package.\n\nThe weight of appearance standards touches nearly everyone. Learning to accept yourself is the central task.\n\nYou could spend a lifetime chasing the newest diet book, or you could simply work with the body you already have. Both routes make up who you are.\n\nThe diet sector pulls in billions of dollars each year, and yet the only honest advice is to eat a little less and move a little more. There is no reason to liquidize your meals or live on cabbage leaves at dawn.\n\nStand in front of the mirror and tell yourself that no one else shares your exact mix of features, and that singular quality makes you beautiful, Miranda Hart has written.",
        wordCount: 193
      },
      {
        title: 'Are we raising a generation of high maintenance kids',
        text: "Some people do not want children, others cannot have them, and neither situation should attract judgment. That said, Miranda has spotted a trend she describes as extreme motherhood.\n\nFolks seem to forget that raising kids has been happening for centuries, and even prehistoric parents managed it somehow. The pile of parenting books swells each year, and Miranda believes everyone needs to take a breath.\n\nModern parents carry enormous pressure to produce the perfect child, and the publishing industry keeps piling on advice. Slow down and focus on the basics instead of comparing your child with anyone else's.\n\nMiranda often finds herself driving past school gates, half-tempted to roll down the window and tell other parents that the world will not end if their child has not globe-trotted by a certain age or hit the usual milestones. Miranda grew up with a stick and a tin can to play with, and she turned out fine.\n\nToday every conversation seems to orbit organic meals, allergies, and avoiding certain ingredients. The whole thing is exhausting.\n\nMiranda has no children of her own, though she serves as a godparent and adores the role. She can take her godchildren out for the day, build block towers with them, and laugh at their jokes. Once a tantrum starts, she can hand them back. Miranda suspects most adults claim to love children yet feel a quiet relief when the day ends and they can be returned.",
        wordCount: 280
      },
      {
        title: 'Hold on to the small dreams that color your week',
        text: "Miranda has never lost the habit of dreaming. At twenty-five she pictured herself joining the Spice Girls as the sixth member, and she still keeps a private hope of one day winning the Wimbledon Singles trophy, including a mental rehearsal of the celebration.\n\nDropping these modest daydreams removes the sparkle from ordinary life. Most of us put on a favorite song and quietly picture ourselves as a stadium-filling rock star. That quick mental detour is part of what makes a day fun, and Miranda wants readers to keep doing it.\n\nLet the imagination keep working. Those tiny hopes carry you through rough patches and lend a little extra backbone when life pushes back.\n\nProof that daydreams can land sits in Miranda's own story. A decade of work that never quite fit has been replaced by a comedy career that does. At thirty-eight, she can finally relax into herself, idiocy and all, on her own terms.\n\nEveryone hits rough stretches, even the people who look untouchable. Plenty of famous faces still feel embarrassed or awkward in private. The only real response is to laugh and move on.\n\nA lot of us feel like outsiders or that we keep getting things wrong. That feeling is more common than you think.",
        wordCount: 222
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "Miranda has turned authenticity into a career. She does not perform a different self, does not bend to outside pressure, and does not worry about whether she lines up with the usual image of a successful female television star. She is a genuinely inspiring example to watch.\n\nLiving honestly is difficult in a culture that constantly judges how you look and act. Building the muscle to shrug off those expectations takes years of practice. Yet being true to yourself can begin today, as can finding laughter in the strange moments that life tends to deliver.\n\nA small set of experiments can help. Notice the playful daydreams that drift through your day, like picturing yourself on a big stage or in your favorite show. Promise to keep them going. If you are chasing the latest diet, try the plain version instead. Eat a little less, move a little more. Each morning, stand in front of the mirror and repeat the line Miranda likes. You are beautiful precisely because no one else is quite like you.",
        wordCount: 208
      }
    ]
  },
  'ivan-ilyin-putin-s-philosopher-of-russian-fascism.json': {
    base: { id: 'ivan-ilyin-putin-s-philosopher-of-russian-fascism', title: 'Ivan Ilyin, Putin’s Philosopher of Russian Fascism', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781662514270 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'How a strange dialogue became the seed of Russian fascism',
        text: "Ivan Ilyin broke with mainstream Christianity. He held that the Creator set out to perfect himself through the world but instead unleashed original sin and slipped away in disgrace. In his view, a modern society that celebrates pluralism and individual rights only multiplies Satan's leverage while God remains banished. History, for Ilyin, was not a coherent story about the present but a moral failure, hollow and corrupt. The sole remaining hope was a virtuous nation led by a single ruler toward total politics, fusing everyone into one undying collective body.\n\nBecause the unifying Word was the only good left in existence, any tactic that promised its restoration was acceptable, Timothy Snyder has observed.\n\nOut of that stance Ilyin built his case for a Russian form of fascism. At its core sat the idea of law, or legal consciousness, though that idea meant different things before and after the 1917 to 1923 upheaval. Before the Revolution, he thought law would help Russians enter a universal mind and become a modern state. After it, he argued that a particular kind of soul, rather than the rational mind, let Russians accept authoritarian commands as legitimate law.\n\nThe Russian Federation appeared long after the Soviet collapse, decades past Ilyin's death. It has never embraced the rule of law as its governing principle. Instead, Russian supremacism applies Ilyin's playbook with both care and invention. To Ilyin, the failure of law became the moral code of twentieth century Russia. In the century that followed, his heirs repackaged economic unfairness as patriotic virtue.\n\nVladimir Putin, the sitting Russian president, leans on Ilyin's geopolitical vision to redirect attention from internal decay toward exporting that morality overseas.\n\nBecause Ilyin recast world politics as a fight over spiritual danger, Russian supremacism now frames the United States, Ukraine, and Europe as civilizational threats to Russia.",
        wordCount: 320
      },
      {
        title: 'Tracing Ilyin\'s early life to make sense of his later doctrine',
        text: "Ivan Ilyin was born in 1883 to a Russian nobleman and a German Protestant mother who joined the Orthodox Church. He studied philosophy in Moscow, where he read Immanuel Kant (1724 to 1804) closely. Even so, he could not recognize ordinary Russians in Kant's picture of rational beings who make meaningful choices. Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel (1770 to 1831) became another anchor, and Ilyin announced a Hegelian revival in 1912, hoping time would smooth every awkward friction.\n\nHistory as a whole is Spirit unfolding in time, just as Nature is the Idea unfolding in space, Hegel once wrote.\n\nIlyin grew sour on the Russian peasantry and on city residents, blaming them for what he labeled sexual perversion.\n\nHe began to doubt that history moved only through Spirit.\n\nIn 1913 he advanced a theory that perversion was a national illness and offered himself to Sigmund Freud (1856 to 1939) as the father of a national psychotherapy. By the time of World War I, Ilyin claimed he could read a metaphysical truth through a physical surface, and he wrote his dissertation on Hegel. He concluded that Hegel's Spirit was simply God, that God had launched history, and that history had locked God out of influence.\n\nIlyin and Lenin began trading ideas in 1917, after Lenin helped him dodge arrest by the Cheka, the Bolshevik security police. They shared Hegel's idea of totality but little else. Lenin, an atheist, framed the central conflict as one between the bourgeoisie and the working class, though he never denied that some good in human nature might survive inside history. Ilyin held the opposite view, treating God's act of creation as the original sin and finding no goodness in the past or in people themselves.\n\nWithout Lenin's revolution, Ilyin would likely have avoided the right-wing political turn his dissertation later took, Timothy Snyder has argued.\n\nLenin's uprising proved to Ilyin that the world was every bit as sinful as he had warned. He concluded that any real political rebirth had to begin in the realm of myth. The nation, he said, needed towering heroes who could impose their will to start reconstruction.\n\nIt was an ideology still looking for a shape and a label, in Timothy Snyder's words.",
        wordCount: 385
      },
      {
        title: 'Why Ilyin adored Mussolini and resented Italy for beating Russia to fascism',
        text: "Ilyin left Russia the year the Soviet Union took shape and traveled to Italy, where Mussolini's fascist state fired his imagination. Ilyin was sure that bold actors could rewrite a broken reality through bold acts. He read Jesus' line about not judging as the cry of a defeated God whose Son had failed. The upright man, by contrast, could see clear good and evil and pick out the enemies who had to be erased.\n\nIlyin treated every day as a day of judgment. Anyone who let an enemy live when destruction was possible would themselves be judged. Until God returned, Ilyin appointed himself the one who named those enemies.\n\nFor Ilyin, loving an enemy also meant its opposite. Love signaled totality. Christianity, in his hands, became the vehicle for a clear-sighted philosopher to unleash violence under the banner of love. He defended the killing of foreigners so a nation could begin the totality politics that might, eventually, bring God back. He rejected Bolshevism as the illness of a broken world rather than the cure, which meant Soviet and European governments needed to be toppled by force.\n\nMy prayer is like a sword. And my sword is like a prayer, Ilyin wrote.\n\nIlyin was bothered that Russians were not the pioneers of fascism. In 1927 he tried to claim that priority by tying the White opposition to the Bolsheviks as the start of the Russian fascist movement. He called those fighters his White brothers, the fascists, and argued that the White Spirit was eternal and turned arbitrary rule into patriotism.\n\nA spirit of lawlessness replaces the spirit of the law, and a spirit of murder replaces the spirit of mercy, Timothy Snyder has written.\n\nIlyin backed Mussolini and Hitler in the early phase of their reigns. He argued that Europe was doomed to collapse and that only figures like Mussolini and Hitler could rescue it. At first he believed that Nazis and Russians shared a common Spirit. After World War II, he shifted and recast the war as a Western assault on Russian purity.",
        wordCount: 365
      },
      {
        title: 'Ilyin\'s blueprint for the perfect tyrant and his regime',
        text: "Ilyin finished his fascist doctrine by declaring Russia the only undefiled nation on earth. From a small region around Moscow, Russia had grown into a model empire. Ilyin insisted that it had spread without aggression and had always been ringed by hostile powers. Russia was the victim, in his telling, because other nations missed the virtue it was defending whenever it seized more land.\n\nIlyin did not let facts get in the way. He argued that Russia was innocent regardless of its actions, and that the Russian take on reality was a kind of untranslatable holiness.\n\nRussia, he wrote, was a single living organism with no room for individuals or constitutions. He published Our Tasks, a set of political essays and constitutional suggestions that Vladimir Putin would later study and apply. The portrait of the ideal national dictator looked like this.\n\nThe leader must arrive from outside ordinary history. He must carry the masculine vigor of a Mussolini. He would act as chief executive, chief legislator, chief judge, and commander of the armed forces. His authority would be unconstrained. Elections would exist only to display the people's submission. Parties would exist only to trap the ambitious. Ordinary citizens could pursue hobbies, but only those that fit the corporate order and could be policed.\n\nIlyin's picture of Russia's return to God required giving up not only individuality and plurality but also basic humanity, in Timothy Snyder's reading.\n\nThe future Ilyin offered his heirs was not about individual freedom. It was the freedom to merge with the whole.",
        wordCount: 261
      },
      {
        title: 'Putin\'s use of Ilyin and the danger it carries',
        text: "Ilyin's dream of a religious totalitarian state never came true, but his ideas helped Vladimir Putin build the authoritarian kleptocracy that Russia is today.\n\nPutin is a former KGB officer who served in East Germany during Soviet times. He became prime minister in 1999 and launched a war in Chechnya almost immediately. In 2000 he won the presidency and held it until 2008, when he handed the office to his ally Dmitry Medvedev.\n\nPutin came back to the presidency four years later and has remained in power, accumulating more than seventeen years of unchecked rule.\n\nUnder Putin, corruption became the operating system of the state. Vladyslav Surkov, the architect of Russian propaganda, borrowed the Western appetite for infotainment to manufacture a reality that celebrated Russian purity.\n\nIn 2005, Putin and Surkov began quoting Ilyin and gave him the title of Kremlin court philosopher. Medvedev pushed Ilyin's work on Russian youth, and much of the storytelling on state television carried his fingerprints.\n\nIlyin has been quoted by the chief justice of the constitutional court, by the foreign minister, and by the senior leaders of the Russian Orthodox Church, Timothy Snyder has noted.\n\nWhen Putin returned to the presidency in 2012, his goal was not to entrench the rule of law at home. It was to push back against neighbors that had built their own paths. The rule of law, Putin insisted, was a Western import, and Russia had to defeat it and stretch from Lisbon to Vladivostok.\n\nThanks to Ilyin, today's Russian leaders treat the former Soviet space as Russia proper.\n\nIlyin always wrote Ukrainians in quotation marks. In his view, Ukraine was part of the Russian organism and could not be split off. He treated any mention of Ukraine as a hostile act.\n\nSince 2012, Russian policy toward Ukraine has run on Ilyin's logic, from the annexation of Crimea to the seizure of parts of Donetsk and Luhansk in the summer of 2014. Ilyin would have cheered the final objective of that war.\n\nIf the world were freed from demonic powers like the United States, life would be easier for everyone, and one day it will happen, Putin has said.\n\nThe key point is that Putin emerged from the realm of myth, just as Ilyin had predicted.",
        wordCount: 381
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing reflections',
        text: "Ivan Ilyin was not the only Russian voice discussing fascism, but he was the most popular and the most quoted. His framework filled a moral vacuum and served political aims, helping Russia slide into the authoritarian kleptocracy we see today.\n\nThe ideas of Kant, Hegel, and Freud fed Ilyin's thinking and shaped his version of fascist theory.\n\nHe treated Russia as a single living organism, free of individuals and constitutions. Our Tasks, his collection of political essays and constitutional recommendations, was later read and used by Vladimir Putin.\n\nIlyin was uneasy that Russians were not the first to put fascism into practice.\n\nTo Ilyin, love was totality. Christianity, in his reading, was the way for a clear-sighted philosopher to spread violence in the name of love. He defended the killing of foreigners so a nation could launch the totality politics that might eventually bring God back.\n\nIlyin closed his theory of fascism by naming Russia the only unblemished nation on earth.\n\nRussia was a perfect empire, perpetually surrounded by attackers. A small patch of land around Moscow grew into the largest country in history without ever launching an offensive. Even as it expanded, Russia was the victim, because Europeans could not grasp the deep virtue it was defending as it took more land, in Timothy Snyder's words.\n\nIn 2014, Europe and the United States slipped up by treating the Russian invasion of Ukraine as a culture clash instead of a serious assault on the rule of law.\n\nIlyin argued that the failure of law became the moral code of twentieth century Russia. In the twenty-first century, his heirs used his ideas to recast economic unfairness as patriotic virtue.",
        wordCount: 295
      }
    ]
  }
};
